result.execSummary:
The defendant Samuel C Hunt was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (3rd), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Samuel C Hunt in court with attorney Michael Jude.  Alyssa M. Schaller appeared for the State of Wisconsin. 

 AS TO BOTH COUNTS: 

Defendant waived rights and pled guilty.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire received and filed.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Parties stipulate to the facts of the complaint as a basis for a guilty plea.  Court found the defendant guilty as charged in the complaint.  Judgment of Conviction entered.

AS TO COUNT ONE:

The Court ordered the Defendant to serve SIX MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence with credit for 1 day time served. NO  Huber privileges  for the first 45 days of the the sentence, remainder of sentence can have huber pursuant to Sec. 303.08 Wis. Stats to apply for spousal care and can be on ES. Sentence to commence forthwith. 

Fine of $600.00  PLUS ALL MANDATORY costs, fees and surcharges from bail and balance  to be paid by 9-25-2018 or serve 60 consecutive days in the House of Correction.

Court ordered defendant's operating privileges revoked for two years with the mandatory reinstatement fee.

AODA assessment and follow through with recommended programming.

Defendant's operating privilege for operation of Class D vehicles is restricted to operating vehicles that are equipped with an ignition interlock device; and each motor vehicle for which the defendant's name appears on the vehicle's certificate of title or registration must be equipped with an ignition interlock device beginning on the date the department issues any license and for a period of  two years  thereafter.
